<ArticleLayout
  title="Garage Tool Storage That Starts With Sorting"
  description="Sort hand tools, power tools and small hardware before choosing drawers, cabinets or wall storage for their weight, use and access needs."
  category="Garage Storage"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/garage.webp"
  imageAlt="An organised garage with wall storage, shelves and clear floor space"
>
  <p>
    The right place for a tool depends on the moment it is needed. A screwdriver used every
    weekend should not be buried beneath power tools, while blades, chemicals and equipment that
    needs controlled access should not be displayed simply because a pegboard looks orderly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lay the collection out by type, weight and frequency of use. Remove broken items and separate
    the small hardware that disappears inside large drawers. Then decide what must travel to a
    job, what can hang and what needs a cabinet or chest.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage follows those decisions. Check drawer depth, wall type, fixings and load ratings,
    and keep the work area and route through the garage clear.
  </p>

  <h2>Lay out the tools before choosing the cabinet</h2>
  <p>
    The tools come before the cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Emptying every tool onto the floor may not be practical, but you can still group tools
    into broad categories before buying storage.
  </p>
  <p>Useful groups include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>hand tools</li>
    <li>power tools</li>
    <li>tool batteries and chargers</li>
    <li>drill bits and driver bits</li>
    <li>screws, nails and fixings</li>
    <li>measuring tools</li>
    <li>gardening hand tools</li>
    <li>painting and decorating tools</li>
    <li>car tools and accessories</li>
    <li>sharp tools and blades</li>
    <li>adhesives, lubricants and chemicals</li>
    <li>rarely used tools</li>
    <li>broken, duplicated or incomplete tools</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This step matters because different tools need different storage. A screwdriver set does
    not need the same storage as a circular saw, a box of drill bits, a paint scraper, a
    battery charger or a container of sharp blades.
  </p>
  <p>
    If everything is treated as one "tool pile", it is easy to buy the wrong storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove duplicates and unusable items first</h2>
  <p>
    Garage tools often build up slowly over years. Many households end up with duplicate
    screwdrivers, old drill bits, half-empty packets of fixings, broken tape measures,
    leftover hardware and tools kept "just in case".
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying new storage, check what should actually stay.
  </p>
  <p>Sort into:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Group</th>
        <th>What it means</th>
        <th>Action</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Keep and use often</td>
        <td>tools used weekly or monthly</td>
        <td>store where they are easy to reach</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Keep but use rarely</td>
        <td>specialist or seasonal tools</td>
        <td>store in labelled drawers, boxes or lower-frequency zones</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Duplicates</td>
        <td>repeated tools that do the same job</td>
        <td>keep the best set and remove extras if not needed</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Incomplete</td>
        <td>missing parts, empty cases, unmatched accessories</td>
        <td>repair, match up or remove</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Broken or damaged</td>
        <td>damaged handles, blunt blades, faulty items</td>
        <td>repair or dispose of appropriately</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hazardous</td>
        <td>sharp blades, chemicals, batteries</td>
        <td>store with extra caution</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Buying more storage before this step can make the garage look tidier without fixing the
    real problem.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate hand tools from power tools</h2>
  <p>
    Hand tools and power tools usually need different storage.
  </p>
  <p>Hand tools may suit:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>pegboards</li>
    <li>drawers</li>
    <li>small cabinets</li>
    <li>wall panels</li>
    <li>tool rolls</li>
    <li>portable toolboxes</li>
    <li>shallow trays</li>
    <li>labelled bins</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Power tools may need:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>deeper shelves</li>
    <li>tool chests</li>
    <li>enclosed cabinets</li>
    <li>original cases</li>
    <li>open cubbies</li>
    <li>lower shelves</li>
    <li>protected storage away from damp or dust where possible</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Power tools can be heavier, bulkier and more awkward than hand tools. They may also have
    batteries, chargers, blades, discs or accessories that need to stay with the tool.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying storage, check whether each power tool is better kept in its case, on a
    shelf, in a drawer, in a cabinet or in a portable toolbox.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort small hardware separately</h2>
  <p>
    Screws, nails, wall plugs, washers, hooks, brackets, drill bits and driver bits can make
    a garage feel messy even when the larger tools are under control.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying a tool cabinet or pegboard, sort small hardware into simple groups.
  </p>
  <p>Common categories include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>screws</li>
    <li>nails</li>
    <li>wall plugs</li>
    <li>bolts and nuts</li>
    <li>washers</li>
    <li>hooks and brackets</li>
    <li>drill bits</li>
    <li>driver bits</li>
    <li>sanding discs or sheets</li>
    <li>spare blades</li>
    <li>picture-hanging hardware</li>
    <li>furniture assembly parts</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Small hardware usually works better in small drawers, divided organisers, labelled
    containers or compartment boxes than loose in a large drawer.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid putting tiny items in deep tubs or open boxes. They become hard to find and often
    end up mixed together again.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what needs portable storage</h2>
  <p>
    Not every tool should be fixed to a wall or cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some tools are used away from the garage. A portable toolbox may be more useful than a
    neat wall display if you regularly work in the house, garden, driveway, carport or at
    another property.
  </p>
  <p>Portable storage may suit:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>basic household repair tools</li>
    <li>commonly used screwdrivers and pliers</li>
    <li>measuring tape, utility knife and level</li>
    <li>drill bits and driver bits</li>
    <li>small fixings</li>
    <li>car tools</li>
    <li>garden repair tools</li>
    <li>tools used for rental maintenance requests or quick jobs</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If a tool is often carried to the job, it may not belong permanently on a pegboard.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good setup can combine fixed garage storage with a small portable kit for common
    tasks.
  </p>

  <h2>Check what needs controlled access</h2>
  <p>
    Tools are not ordinary clutter. Some items should be stored where children, pets or
    visitors cannot easily access them.
  </p>
  <p>Items needing more caution may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>sharp tools</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>saws</li>
    <li>knives</li>
    <li>chisels</li>
    <li>power tools</li>
    <li>batteries</li>
    <li>chargers</li>
    <li>adhesives</li>
    <li>solvents</li>
    <li>lubricants</li>
    <li>pesticides</li>
    <li>paint products</li>
    <li>heavy tools</li>
    <li>small fixings that could be swallowed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying open shelving or pegboards, decide which items should be enclosed,
    locked, kept higher, kept lower, or stored separately.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume an open wall system is suitable for every tool. Open storage can be
    convenient, but it may not be appropriate for sharp, hazardous or easily misused items.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure wall space before buying a pegboard</h2>
  <p>
    Pegboards and wall panels can work well for hand tools, but only if the wall and layout
    suit them.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a pegboard, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>available wall width</li>
    <li>available wall height</li>
    <li>bench height, if installed above a workbench</li>
    <li>distance from car doors or walkways</li>
    <li>nearby shelves, doors and switches</li>
    <li>whether tools will protrude into the walkway</li>
    <li>whether the garage door track affects the area</li>
    <li>whether lighting is good enough</li>
    <li>whether the wall type suits the fixing method</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Also check what the pegboard or panel is rated to hold. A pegboard for light hand tools
    is different from a heavy-duty wall system.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume a pegboard can hold heavy tools, power tools or awkward items unless the
    product instructions and load ratings support that use.
  </p>

  <h2>Check wall type and fixing requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Wall-mounted tool storage needs careful checking.
  </p>
  <p>
    Garage walls may be plasterboard, brick, block, concrete, timber-framed, steel-framed,
    lined, partly lined or part of a shared wall. Some walls may have pipes, wiring or other
    services behind them.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying wall-mounted tool storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>what type of wall you have</li>
    <li>what fixings the product requires</li>
    <li>whether the product needs studs, masonry fixings or another method</li>
    <li>load ratings</li>
    <li>installation instructions</li>
    <li>whether drilling is allowed</li>
    <li>whether body corporate approval is needed</li>
    <li>whether qualified installation is appropriate</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Renters should check the lease and ask for approval before drilling or permanently
    fixing storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the product needs a fixing method that does not suit your wall or rental situation,
    choose another storage option.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure cabinet and drawer sizes carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Tool cabinets can look large from the outside but still have drawers that do not suit
    your tools.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a cabinet, tool chest or drawer unit, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>longest hand tools</li>
    <li>tallest tools</li>
    <li>power-tool cases</li>
    <li>battery chargers</li>
    <li>drill bit cases</li>
    <li>socket sets</li>
    <li>clamps</li>
    <li>extension leads</li>
    <li>sanding gear</li>
    <li>safety gear</li>
    <li>manuals or accessories you want to keep with tools</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Check drawer height as well as drawer width. Many tools need more vertical clearance
    than expected.
  </p>
  <p>Also check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>drawer load ratings</li>
    <li>whether drawers can open fully in the garage position</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet blocks a walkway</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet needs anchoring</li>
    <li>whether it can sit level on the floor</li>
    <li>whether castors are suitable for the floor</li>
    <li>whether it can be moved when loaded</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A cabinet is only useful if the tools fit properly and the drawers can open where the
    cabinet will actually stand.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan around the workbench if you have one</h2>
  <p>
    If the garage has a workbench, tool storage should support that area rather than compete
    with it.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>bench width and depth</li>
    <li>available wall space above the bench</li>
    <li>lighting</li>
    <li>power-point position</li>
    <li>drawer or cabinet access</li>
    <li>where tools will sit during a project</li>
    <li>whether open shelves above the bench will get in the way</li>
    <li>whether sharp or heavy tools need controlled storage</li>
    <li>whether small parts can be contained</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A pegboard above a workbench can work well for frequently used hand tools. A cabinet
    below or beside the bench may suit heavier tools or items that need doors. Small drawers
    or divided organisers can help with screws, bits and fixings.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid filling the benchtop with storage containers. A workbench needs clear working
    space.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully about batteries and chargers</h2>
  <p>
    Many garages store cordless tool batteries and chargers. These should not be treated as
    ordinary loose accessories.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before planning a charging or battery storage area, check the power-tool manufacturer's
    guidance and product instructions. Consider heat, moisture, dust, ventilation, cable
    placement and whether the area is protected from accidental knocks or spills.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not create makeshift electrical setups or overloaded charging areas. Avoid placing
    chargers where cables cross walkways or where they may be exposed to water, dust,
    chemicals or damage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you are unsure about a suitable charging setup, follow manufacturer guidance or seek
    appropriate advice.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep sharp tools and blades controlled</h2>
  <p>
    Sharp tools need deliberate storage.
  </p>
  <p>These may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>saws</li>
    <li>chisels</li>
    <li>knives</li>
    <li>utility blades</li>
    <li>drill bits</li>
    <li>scraper blades</li>
    <li>gardening blades</li>
    <li>plane blades</li>
    <li>cutting discs</li>
    <li>multi-tool blades</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying open storage, decide whether sharp items should be in cases, drawers,
    cabinets, blade holders or labelled containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid loose blades in general drawers. Avoid storing sharp tools where children can
    reach them or where someone may grab them without seeing the edge.
  </p>
  <p>
    For households with children or pets, controlled storage is usually more important than
    display-style storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider dust, moisture and pests</h2>
  <p>
    Garages are often less sealed than indoor rooms. Tools can be affected by moisture,
    dust, pests and temperature changes.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, check whether your garage has:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>damp corners</li>
    <li>water entry under the door</li>
    <li>condensation</li>
    <li>mould-prone areas</li>
    <li>heavy dust</li>
    <li>pest activity</li>
    <li>direct sun or heat</li>
    <li>poor airflow</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Open pegboards can make tools easy to see, but they may not protect against dust or
    moisture. Enclosed cabinets may protect tools better in some garages, but they still
    need to suit the items being stored.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing tools directly on damp floors. Keep valuable or sensitive tools inside the
    home if the garage is unsuitable.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid turning tool storage into display storage</h2>
  <p>
    A neat wall of tools can look appealing, but it should not come before practical use.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying display-style storage, ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>are these tools used often enough to need visible storage?</li>
    <li>will they stay clean and dry on the wall?</li>
    <li>are they light enough for the system?</li>
    <li>will they be controlled and easy to remove?</li>
    <li>will they protrude into the walkway?</li>
    <li>should some tools be enclosed instead?</li>
    <li>will the setup still work when new tools are added?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A pegboard is useful when it makes tools easier to find and return. It is less useful if
    it becomes a decorative wall that does not match how the household actually uses tools.
  </p>

  <h2>Tool storage that looks better than it works</h2>
  <p>Avoid these mistakes before buying:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying a cabinet before measuring the tools</li>
    <li>choosing pegboards without checking wall type</li>
    <li>putting heavy tools on light-duty hooks</li>
    <li>storing sharp tools in open reach of children</li>
    <li>keeping batteries and chargers in unsuitable areas</li>
    <li>mixing tiny hardware in large drawers</li>
    <li>storing frequently used tools behind rarely used items</li>
    <li>using the workbench as permanent storage</li>
    <li>buying drawers that are too shallow</li>
    <li>placing cabinets where drawers cannot fully open</li>
    <li>ignoring moisture, dust or pests</li>
    <li>assuming all tools should be displayed</li>
    <li>using wall storage where portable storage would be better</li>
    <li>blocking switches, taps, meters or walkways</li>
    <li>keeping broken or duplicate tools because storage space exists</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Tool storage should make tools easier to use and return properly.
  </p>

  <h2>Test reach, weight and controlled access</h2>
  <p>Before buying garage tool storage, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>which tools are used most often</li>
    <li>which tools need portable storage</li>
    <li>which tools are heavy</li>
    <li>which tools are sharp</li>
    <li>which items need controlled access</li>
    <li>which tools are duplicated or broken</li>
    <li>size of power-tool cases</li>
    <li>drawer height needed</li>
    <li>cabinet depth and drawer opening clearance</li>
    <li>wall width and height for pegboards</li>
    <li>wall type and fixing requirements</li>
    <li>load ratings for hooks, shelves or panels</li>
    <li>workbench position</li>
    <li>power-point and lighting locations</li>
    <li>battery and charger storage needs</li>
    <li>moisture, dust and pest issues</li>
    <li>child and pet access risks</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before shopping. Tool storage is much easier to choose when the tools
    are sorted first.
  </p>

  <h2>Let the tools choose the storage</h2>
  <p>
    Garage tool storage should start with sorting, not buying.
  </p>
  <p>
    Separate hand tools, power tools, small hardware, sharp items, batteries, chargers and
    hazardous products before choosing cabinets or pegboards. Then measure the wall, floor,
    drawer sizes, load requirements and access paths.
  </p>
  <p>
    For many households, the best setup will combine a few simple options: a portable
    toolbox for common tasks, drawers for small hardware, lower storage for heavier tools,
    and cautious wall storage for suitable hand tools.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a storage system makes tools harder to use, exposes sharp items, blocks access,
    overloads a wall, or ignores moisture and child access, it is not the right solution.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is not to display every tool. The goal is to keep the tools you actually use
    organised, accessible and controlled.
  </p>

